To achieve the elemental compositions of the TiO2, TiO2-peroxo, and TiO2-peroxo/C-Dots (0.75 mL) photocatalysts, EDX analysis was performed (Fig. 2
                     ). The EDX spectra of the TiO2 and TiO2-peroxo samples revealed the existence of Ti and O elements. From the EDX spectrum of the binary nanocomposite, Ti, O, and C signals were detected. Weight percentages of the elements in these photocatalysts are shown in Table 1
                     . Moreover, to study the distribution uniformity, EDX elemental mappings of the TiO2-peroxo/C-Dots (0.75 mL) sample are shown in Fig. 2(b-e). From these images, it can be noticed that Ti, O, and C elements have uniformly presented in the photocatalyst. Indeed, the results clearly show that the elements are randomly distributed in the TiO2-peroxo/C-Dots (0.75 mL) sample.

The band gap energies of the TiO2 and TiO2-peroxo photocatalysts were determined by Tauc plots, as displayed in Fig. 9
                     a. As observed, the band gap energies decreased from 3.2 eV to 2.9 eV, with the treatment of TiO2 with H2O2. The electronic properties of the TiO2 and TiO2-peroxo photocatalysts were investigated by Mott–Schottky method (Fig. 9b, c). The slopes of Mott-Schottky plots are positive, suggesting that both of the samples are n-type semiconductors [44]. The flat-band potentials (Efb
                     ) for the TiO2 and TiO2-peroxo are estimated to be −0.6 eV vs. Ag/AgCl (−0.4 and −0.4 eV vs. NHE). The Efb
                      for n-type semiconductor is more positive by ∼0.1 eV than the conduction band potentials (ECB
                     ) [45]. So ECB
                      for the TiO2 and TiO2-peroxo are approximately −0.5 eV. According to the formula: E
                     VB = E
                     CB + Eg, the valence band potentials (EVB
                     ) for the TiO2 and TiO2-peroxo are equal to 2.7 eV and 2.4 eV, respectively.
